Multivariate Fish Analysis

Nick Toimieri

1 Import and manipulate data

  • Combined 2015 and 2016-2019 data
  • Corrected some spp codes
  • Make a ‘group’ variable for lumping taxa/species
  • No depth data for the 2015 data.
    • I took the average of the quadrats.
    • I assigned transects with an average depth of >20 ft to the 10-m group.

NOTE: Transects with visibility < 2.2 m were deleted from the analysis.

NOTE: These analyses include 2015.

DATA TRANSFORM: none

NOTES

  • Some rockfish were recorded in the ‘adult’ category (eg SECA instead of SECAy) but were small.
  • Set minimum size for rockfishes to 6 cm. Fish <= to 6 cm were classified as YOY.
  • Maintained their original desigation in SPECIES column. New designation in the ‘group’ column.

Species included and the higher grouping used in the analyses are:

3.1.2 CAP

3.1.3 capscale - site x year x depth

  • Used this because capscale produces species scores.
  • Capscale is more of and rds approach.
  • Produces cleaner and nicer plots than CAPdiscrim. I would use this.

For the first set of ordinations, I ran the stats on a model with year, site, depth. The third pane averages the results by year x site for clarity. The ordination is qualitively similar to the next capscale, which is just a bit more clear.

Ordination plot for CAP based on site x year x depth. Error bars are +/- 1.0 s.e.

3.1.4 Site x Year

capscale analysis but with year x site as groups

Ordination plot for CAP based on site x year x depth. Error bars are +/- 1.0 s.e.

3.1.5 capscale - sites only

This analysis uses only sites as the category in the initial rda analyses. The results are more clear and consistent with all the previous ones.

Since we are largely interested in site differences, I think we could use this or the nMDS plots to summarize the fish community.

Note, however, that there was significant multivariate dispersion (p = 0, differences in multivariate variance). So some of the difference has to do with some sites being more variable than others.

Ordination plot for CAP based on site x year x depth. Error bars are +/- 1.0 s.e.

4 Fish - Habitat Associations

4.1 CAP fish vs habitat by zone

I think the site x year x zone makes the most sense here:

  • Habitat and fish were not on the same transects
  • Site x Depth x Year is the smallest scale association of fish vs habitat
  • Site x Depth x Year gives us the most data to use for the ordinations
  • Site x Depth x Year gets the closes to spp vs habitat associations

There was a significant relationship between fish assembalge structure and abiotic habitat, defined here as the combination of substrate type and relief.

The primary result here seems to be that yellowtail rockfish YOY like high relief habitat with boulder and greater than a 2-m relief. The same is true to some extent for bait fish. I think we can take the yellowtail results to univariate analyses as one of the interesting outcomes of the multivariate perusal of the data.
